07333nam a22008535i 9781575066899DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750668997 a10.1515/97815750668992doi  a(DE-B1597)584028  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBS1198.P76 2013eb 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a221.95007200aProphets, Prophecy, and Ancient Israelite Historiography /ced. by Lissa Wray Beal, Mark J. Boda. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (412 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1 Prophets and Prophecy in Israelite Historiographic Books -- t"Face to Face": Moses as Prophet in Exodus 11:1-12:28 -- tThe Shaping of a Prophet: Joshua in the Deuteronomistic History -- tRecycling Heaven's Words: Receiving and Retrieving Divine Revelation in the Historiography of Judges -- tSamuel Agonistes: A Conflicted Prophet's Resistance to God and Contribution to the Failure of Israel's First King -- tProphecy as Prediction in Biblical Historiography -- tJeroboam and the Prophets in 1 Kings 11-14: Prophetic Word for Two Kingdoms -- tPresumptuous Prophets Participating in a Deuteronomic Debate -- tProphecy Influencing History: Dialogism in the Chronicler's Ahaz Narrative -- tChronicles and Its Reshaping of Memories of Monarchic Period Prophets: Some Observations -- tDeus ex Machina and Plot Construction in Ezra 1-6 -- tIs the Governor Also among the Prophets? Parsing the Purposes of Jeremiah in the Memory of Nehemiah -- tThe Use and Non-Use of Prophetic Literature in Hellenistic Jewish Historiography -- tPart 2 Historiography in Israelite Prophetic Books -- tThe Poetics of History and the Prophecy of Deutero-Isaiah -- tPersonal Missives and National History: The Relationship between Jeremiah 29 and 36 -- tEzekiel's Perspective of Israel's History: Selective Revisionism? -- tThe Ordering of the Twelve as Israel's Historiography -- tThe "Exilic" Prophecy of Daniel 7: Does It Reflect Late Pre-Maccabean or Early Hellenistic Historiography? -- t(Re)Visionary History: Historiography and Religious Identity in the Animal Apocalypse -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 18 essays by members of the Canadian Society for Biblical Studies published in this volume showcase the work of leading authorities on ancient Israelite and Jewish historiography as it intersects with the phenomenon of prophecy. A deep divide exists between the traditions of historiography and prophecy in the academic study of the Hebrew Bible, and the concern of the contributors is to close that gap, to expose the close relationship between these two traditions in the literature of the Hebrew Bible.The first section of the book explores prophecy and prophets in ancient Israelite and Jewish historiographic books (Torah, Deuteronomistic History, Chronicles, Ezra-Nehemiah, Second Temple Jewish historiography). The second section surveys historiography in Israelite and Jewish prophetic books (Isaiah, Jeremiah, Ezekiel, Book of the Twelve, Daniel, 1 Enoch). The contributors engage diverse methodological perspectives in these studies, the goal first being to show the role that the prophets played within the great Hebrew historiographic works and, second, to demonstrate the role that historiography plays within the great Hebrew prophetic works; this makes it clear that the influence is bidirectional.Prophets, Prophecy, and Ancient Israelite Historiography will be of value for advanced students and scholars working on historiographic and prophetic materials in the ancient Israelite and Jewish traditions, featuring the best of research and analysis and interacting with many major ancient literary traditions of historiography and prophecy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aBeal, Lissa Wray, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeal, Lissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoda, Mark J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoda, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuperreault, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFried, Lisbeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKo, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorner, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Bernon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeuchter, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiddleton, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoll, K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOeste, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPitts, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeters, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShepherd, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToffelmire, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZvi, Ehud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org